    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, when you make a student loan payment, it’s divided into two main parts: interest and principal. The interest is calculated based on the current balance and the interest rate, while the principal is what you actually pay back. So, even if you're making the full monthly payments, most of that payment initially goes toward paying the interest, with only a small portion going to reduce the principal balance. This is why it can feel like the balance barely moves at first. As you continue to pay, more of your payment will go toward the principal, and the interest paid will decrease.",
